learning_outcomes.en:
By the end of this course, students will:
- compare and contrast the varying security dynamics shaping international relations in the Asia-Pacific;
- analyse the influence of China as a rising power on East Asia's regional security dynamics as well as the issues that shape China's relations with high-profile neighbours such as Japan, Taiwan and South Korea; 
- analyse the complicated security situation along the Korean Peninsula;
- distinguish security and integration politics that define a regional organization of rising global importance, ASEAN;
- thoroughly define the position and potential of ASEAN in the context of the wider Asian, Chinese, E.U. and U.S. positions in international affairs;
- write critical, argumentative and scholarly discussion and research papers on important Asia-Pacific security topics.

learning_outcomes.et:
Aine läbides üliõpilane:
-	Võrdleb ja vastandab piirkonna erinevaid rahvusvaheliste suhete kujundamise tegureid
-	Analüüsib Hiina võimutõusu dünaamikat Ida-Aasia piirkonnas ning tegureid, mis kujundavad Hiina teravdatud suhted naabririikidega sh Jaapan, taiwan ja Lõuna-Korea; samuti analüüsib keerulist julgeolekuolukorra Korea poolsaarel;
-	Eristab julgeoleku ja integratsiooni poliitikad, mis määratlevad globaalse tähtsusega piirkondliku organisatsiooni (ASEAN) kujunemist;
-	Põhjalikult defineerib ASEAN-i rahvusvaheliste suhete positsioone ja potentsiaali laiemas Aasia kontekstis, Hiinas, EL-s ja USA-s;
-	Kirjutab akadeemilist teadustööd kriitiliselt ja argumenteeritult Aasia-Vaikse ookeani regiooni julgeoleku teemadel.

independent_work.et:
Students are required to do the following: 
1. Undertake all required readings prescribed for this course;
2. Participate actively in lectures and seminars, which requires planning and preparation of questions for in-class discussions;
3. Plan and prepare for written work assessment components;
4. Complete the two written assessments  assigned for this course: a) an argumentative policy paper (not exceeding 2500 words) on the specific incident affecting the regional dynamics in the longrun, b) a report, reflecting on the knowledge gained in the course to assess the future challenges likely to have an ongoing influence in shaping the Asia-Pacific region. The reflection paper should not exceed 4000 words and must carry full academic reference.

description.et:
Students must complete an argumentative policy paper (not exceeding 2500 words) on the specific incident affecting the regional dynamics in the longrun. Assessment is differentiated according to the following criteria:
E - the form is, in general, in compliance with the requirements and correct; references are minimal and insecure; the elements of analysis and independent interpreting are there; the coverage of the subject is, in general, logical, but the connections are full of gaps;
D - the form is in compliance with the requirements and, in general, correct; references are minimal, but relevant; the analysis and independent interpreting is understandable, but at times insecure; the coverage of the subject is logical and associated;
C - the form is in compliance with the requirements and correct; references are relevant and sufficient; analytical connections and interpretations are proper and there is certainty in creating connections; the treatment of the subject is logical, but there are some weaknesses from the point of view of the whole;
B - the form is excellent; the choice, amount and association of references with the text is very good; thorough analysis of connections and references; bold interpretation based on connections; the treatment of the subject as a whole is logical and smooth;
A - the form is excellent; the choice, amount and association of references with the text is creative; the depth of the analysis and the level of independent interpretation is remarkable; the connections are thorough-going and creative; the treatment of the subject is innovative and logical; the text is a remarkable achievement on the whole.
